    full: "The straight line method is the simplest and most common method of depreciation. It assumes that the asset provides equal benefit each year. The formula is: (Cost - Scrap Value) / Useful Life in years. For example, an asset costing ₦100,000 with a scrap value of ₦10,000 and a useful life of 5 years would have annual depreciation of (₦100,000 - ₦10,000) / 5 = ₦18,000 every year. The reducing balance method charges a fixed percentage each year on the reducing balance, so the amount decreases over time. The sum of years digits method gives higher depreciation in early years. The units of production method charges based on how much the asset is used."
