    e: "Land has an unlimited useful life and does not deteriorate over time. Therefore, it is not depreciated. Buildings, machinery, and vehicles have limited useful lives and are depreciated.",
    full: "Land is unique among fixed assets because it does not wear out, become obsolete, or get used up. A piece of land can last forever. Therefore, according to accounting rules, land is not depreciated. However, buildings on the land are depreciated because they have a limited useful life (they wear out, need repairs, and eventually may need to be replaced). Other assets like machinery, equipment, furniture, vehicles, computers, and office equipment all have limited useful lives and are depreciated. Natural resources (like oil wells or timber forests) are not depreciated - they are depleted (a similar concept). Intangible assets (like patents and copyrights) are amortized (also similar to depreciation). Land improvements (like paving, fencing, or landscaping) may be depreciated if they have a limited useful life."
