    full: "Capital reserves are reserves that come from capital transactions rather than from trading profits. They cannot be distributed to shareholders as dividends. Examples of capital reserves include: share premium (excess received over the nominal value of shares), revaluation surplus (increase in asset values when revalued), capital redemption reserve (created when shares are bought back), and retained profits from capital gains. Revenue reserves come from trading profits and can be distributed as dividends. Retained profit is a revenue reserve. Accumulated depreciation is not a reserve - it is a contra-asset. Loss on forfeited shares is a loss, not a reserve. Share premium is a very common capital reserve. It can be used for bonus share issues, writing off preliminary expenses, or writing off share issue costs, but not for dividend payments."
