    full: "When a company issues shares, it may ask shareholders to pay in installments. The process usually works like this: The company authorizes a certain amount of capital. It issues some of that capital. It then 'calls up' a portion of the issued capital, asking shareholders to pay. The called-up capital is what has been requested. The paid-up capital is what has actually been received. If all shareholders pay when asked, called-up capital equals paid-up capital. But if some shareholders fail to pay, paid-up capital is less than called-up capital. The unpaid portion is shown as 'calls in arrears' (a reduction from called-up capital) on the balance sheet. Paid-up capital is important because it represents the actual funds the company has received from shareholders."
