    full: "Preference shares are called 'preference' because they have preferences over ordinary shares in two main areas. First, preference shareholders receive their fixed dividend before ordinary shareholders receive any dividend. If the company has limited profits, ordinary shareholders may get nothing while preference shareholders get their full dividend. Second, if the company goes into liquidation, preference shareholders get their capital back before ordinary shareholders (but after creditors). However, preference shareholders typically do not have voting rights (unless their dividends are in arrears for a certain period). They also do not have the right to attend all meetings or manage the company. Preference shares are a hybrid between equity shares and debt. Some preference shares are cumulative (unpaid dividends accumulate) or participating (share in extra profits)."
