    full: "Cumulative preference shares have an important feature: if the company does not have enough profit to pay the preference dividend in any year, the unpaid dividend is not lost. Instead, it 'accumulates' (builds up) and becomes 'dividends in arrears'. In future years, when profits are available, the company must pay all accumulated arrears before paying any dividend to ordinary shareholders. This provides security to preference shareholders. For example, if a company fails to pay a ₦10,000 preference dividend for two years, it would owe ₦20,000 in arrears. In the third year, it must pay the current year's dividend of ₦10,000 plus the ₦20,000 arrears (total ₦30,000) before ordinary shareholders get anything. Non-cumulative preference shares do not have this feature - any unpaid dividend is lost forever. Most preference shares issued today are cumulative."
