    full: "The Profit and Loss Account (or Income Statement) shows the income and expenses of a business for a period. It includes: sales revenue, cost of sales, gross profit, operating expenses (like rent, salaries, electricity, discount allowed, bad debts, depreciation), other income (like discount received, commission received), interest expenses, and finally net profit or loss. The Balance Sheet shows assets, liabilities, and capital at a specific date. Assets include premises (fixed asset), debtors (current asset), stock, cash, etc. Liabilities include creditors, bank overdraft (current liability), loans, etc. Capital includes owner's investment and retained profits. Discount allowed is an expense because the business is giving up some of the amount owed by customers (offering a discount for early payment). This reduces profit, so it goes in the Profit and Loss Account."
