    full: "Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) is a very important figure. It represents the direct cost of the goods that the business sold during the period. It is calculated as: Opening Stock (goods on hand at the beginning) + Purchases (goods bought during the period) - Closing Stock (goods still on hand at the end). The goods that were not sold are still in stock, so they are not included in COGS. In this example: Opening stock ₦20,000 + Purchases ₦100,000 = Goods Available for Sale ₦120,000. This means the business had goods worth ₦120,000 that could have been sold. At the end, ₦30,000 worth of goods are still in stock. Therefore, the cost of the goods that were actually sold is ₦120,000 - ₦30,000 = ₦90,000. COGS is subtracted from Sales Revenue to calculate Gross Profit."
