    full: "In traditional accounting, the Trading Account and Profit and Loss Account are separate but related. The Trading Account calculates the gross profit. It includes: Sales Revenue, Sales Returns, Opening Stock, Purchases, Purchases Returns, Carriage Inwards, Closing Stock, and Cost of Goods Sold. The result is Gross Profit. The Profit and Loss Account (P&L) then takes the gross profit and deducts all operating expenses to arrive at Net Profit. In modern accounting, these are often combined into a single 'Income Statement'. The Balance Sheet is a separate statement showing assets, liabilities, and capital at a point in time. The Income and Expenditure Account is used by non-profit organizations instead of a Profit and Loss Account. The Trading Account is important because it focuses specifically on the buying and selling activities of the business, helping management see if their pricing and purchasing strategies are effective."
