    h: "Carriage inwards is added to purchases.",
    e: "Carriage inwards is the cost of transporting goods into the business. It is considered part of the cost of purchasing the goods, so it is added to the purchases figure in the trading account.",
    full: "Carriage (transportation) costs are divided into two types. Carriage inwards is the cost of bringing goods into the business. This is a cost directly related to acquiring the goods, so it is treated as part of the cost of purchases. In the Trading Account, we add carriage inwards to purchases to get the total cost of goods available for sale. For example, if purchases are ₦100,000 and carriage inwards is ₦5,000, total cost of purchases is ₦105,000. Carriage outwards is the cost of delivering goods to customers. This is a selling expense, not part of the cost of goods. Carriage outwards is shown as an operating expense in the Profit and Loss Account. The distinction is important because carriage inwards affects gross profit, while carriage outwards affects net profit only."
