    e: "Discount received (getting a discount from a supplier for early payment) is income, so it is shown on the credit side of the Profit and Loss Account. Expenses like rent, salaries, and discount allowed are shown on the debit side.",
    full: "The Profit and Loss Account follows the same basic rules as any ledger account. Debit side = expenses and losses. Credit side = income and gains. Common items on the DEBIT side: rent, salaries, electricity, insurance, depreciation, carriage outwards, discount allowed, bad debts, interest paid, and other operating expenses. Common items on the CREDIT side: sales revenue, discount received, commission received, rent received, interest received, and other income. When a business receives a discount from a supplier for paying early, this is a reduction in the cost of purchases. It is treated as income (credit side). When a business gives a discount to a customer for early payment, this is an expense (debit side). Understanding which side each item belongs to is essential for correctly preparing financial statements."
