    full: "The balance sheet is different from the profit and loss account. The Profit and Loss Account shows performance over a period of time (e.g., the year ended 31 December 2023). It summarizes all the income and expenses for that period. The Balance Sheet shows the position at a specific moment (e.g., at the close of business on 31 December 2023). It lists what the business owns (assets) and what it owes (liabilities), with the difference being the owner's equity (capital). Because the balance sheet is a snapshot, it can change the very next day as transactions occur. For example, if a business pays a bill on 1 January 2024, the cash asset decreases and the liability decreases, so the balance sheet on 2 January would be different. This is why balance sheets always have a specific date, such as 'as at 31 December 2023'. Users can compare balance sheets from different dates to see how the financial position has changed over time."
