    e: "Fixed assets are shown at net book value (cost minus accumulated depreciation). This follows the historical cost concept and the prudence concept.",
    full: "Fixed assets (non-current assets) are usually shown on the balance sheet at their net book value (NBV). The NBV is calculated as: Original Cost - Accumulated Depreciation. For example, a machine bought for ₦100,000 with accumulated depreciation of ₦30,000 would be shown at ₦70,000. This is not the same as market value (what the asset could be sold for) or replacement cost (what it would cost to buy a similar new asset). The historical cost concept says assets should be recorded at their original cost. The prudence concept says we should not overstate asset values. Using NBV is a prudent approach because it shows a conservative value. Some accounting standards allow revaluation of certain fixed assets to their current market value, but this is less common. Most businesses show fixed assets at NBV on the balance sheet, with additional notes giving details of cost, accumulated depreciation, and any revaluations."
