    full: "The quick ratio (also called the acid test ratio) is a more conservative measure of liquidity than the current ratio. It excludes stock (inventory) from current assets because stock may take time to sell and may not be sold at full value. The formula is: Quick Ratio = (Current Assets - Stock) / Current Liabilities. For example, if current assets are ₦500,000 (including stock of ₦200,000) and current liabilities are ₦250,000, the quick ratio is (₦500,000 - ₦200,000) / ₦250,000 = ₦300,000 / ₦250,000 = 1.2:1. A quick ratio of 1:1 or higher is generally considered good, meaning the business has enough liquid assets (excluding stock) to cover its short-term debts. Industries with fast-moving stock (like supermarkets) might have lower quick ratios because stock sells quickly. Industries with slow-moving stock (like car dealerships) need higher quick ratios because stock takes longer to convert to cash. The quick ratio is a good test of immediate solvency."
