    full: "Bank charges are fees the bank charges for maintaining the account, processing transactions, providing statements, etc. These charges appear on the bank statement but may not have been recorded in the business's cash book yet. Bank charges reduce the bank balance (they are a deduction from the account). Therefore, to update the cash book, we need to subtract the bank charges from the cash book balance. The journal entry in the cash book would be: Debit Bank Charges (expense) and Credit Bank (asset). This reduces the cash book balance. After making this entry, the cash book balance will match the bank statement balance (after also adjusting for other items like unpresented cheques and uncredited deposits). Other items that are often subtracted from the cash book balance include: direct debits, standing orders, and interest on overdraft. Items added to the cash book balance include: interest received, dividends received, and direct credits from customers."
