    e: "Recording 1,000 instead of 10,000 is reversing the digits (1 and 0 were transposed). This is called a transposition error. The difference of 9,000 is divisible by 9, which is characteristic of transposition errors.",
    full: "A transposition error occurs when two digits are accidentally reversed (swapped). In this case, ₦10,000 was recorded as ₦1,000 - the '1' and the '0' were transposed. The difference between the correct amount and the recorded amount is ₦9,000. A key characteristic of transposition errors is that the difference is always divisible by 9 (9,000 ÷ 9 = 1,000). This is a useful clue when searching for errors in the trial balance or when reconciling. Transposition errors are common because people often reverse digits when typing. Other types of errors include: omission (forgetting to record a transaction), commission (recording in the wrong account), principle (recording against accounting principles), and compensating (two errors that cancel each other out). To correct a transposition error, you make an adjusting entry. In this case, you would debit the supplier account (increase the amount owed) and credit the suspense account (if the trial balance was affected), or adjust the cash book directly."
