    yr: "2024",
    h: "Bank reconciliation explains the difference between cash book and bank statement.",
    e: "The main purpose of a bank reconciliation statement is to explain the reasons for the difference between the balance in the cash book (bank column) and the balance on the bank statement. It also helps identify errors and update the cash book.",
    full: "Bank reconciliation has several important purposes. First, it explains the difference between the cash book balance and the bank statement balance. This difference is caused by timing differences (unpresented cheques, uncredited deposits) and items not yet recorded in the cash book (bank charges, direct debits, interest). Second, it helps identify errors made by the business (e.g., transposition errors, omitted transactions) or by the bank (e.g., incorrect charges or credits). Third, it provides a list of adjustments that need to be made to the cash book. After making these adjustments, the cash book balance should equal the adjusted bank statement balance. Fourth, it acts as a control measure, helping to prevent and detect fraud. Regular bank reconciliation (monthly) is considered good accounting practice and is often required by auditors and regulators. It is not primarily for finding bank errors (though it can), nor for calculating bank charges (though these are identified during reconciliation)."
