    full: "A direct debit is an instruction from the business to its bank allowing a third party to withdraw money from the account. Common examples include utility bills, insurance premiums, loan repayments, and subscriptions. When a direct debit appears on the bank statement but has not been recorded in the cash book, we must update the cash book. The payment reduces the bank balance, so we credit the Bank account in the cash book. The debit entry depends on what the payment is for. If it's for electricity, we debit Electricity expense. If it's for a loan repayment, we debit Loan account (reducing the liability). If we are unsure, we might use a Suspense account temporarily. The journal entry is: Debit [Appropriate Expense/Liability Account], Credit Bank. This reduces the cash book balance to match the bank statement. After recording all such items (direct debits, standing orders, bank charges, interest), the cash book balance should agree with the adjusted bank statement balance."
