    e: "When a cheque is returned marked 'refer to drawer' (RTD) or 'insufficient funds', it means the customer's bank account does not have enough money to cover the cheque. The cheque is 'bounced' or 'dishonored'.",
    full: "'Refer to drawer' (RTD) is a bank's way of saying 'ask the person who wrote the cheque' - usually because there are not enough funds in their account. This is also called a 'dishonored cheque' or 'bounced cheque'. When this happens, the bank will not pay the cheque, and it will be returned to the business. The business must then reverse the entry it made when it deposited the cheque. The entry was: Debit Bank (increasing the bank balance), Credit Debtors (reducing what the customer owed). When the cheque bounces, the business must reverse this: Debit Debtors (the customer still owes the money), Credit Bank (the bank balance is reduced by the amount of the bounced cheque). The business may also charge the customer a fee for the bounced cheque. Other reasons for cheques being returned include: the cheque being post-dated (dated in the future), the cheque being stale (more than 6 months old), the signature not matching, or the account being closed. 'Refer to drawer' is most commonly associated with insufficient funds."
