    full: "When a partnership is dissolved (wound up), all assets are sold and all liabilities are paid. The realisation account is used to record the process of converting assets to cash and paying liabilities. If a partner decides to take over an asset (instead of selling it to an outsider), the transaction is recorded as: Debit the partner's capital account (with the agreed value of the asset), Credit the realisation account (removing the asset from the realisation process). This reduces the partner's capital by the value of the asset taken, and closes the asset out of the realisation account. The agreed value should be fair and agreed by all partners. If the agreed value is more than the asset's book value, the difference is a profit on realisation and will be shared among partners. If it is less, it is a loss. The alternative wrong entries (Dr Realisation, Cr Partner's Capital) would increase the partner's capital, which is incorrect. The other options are not the standard accounting treatment for dissolution."
