    e: "Profit ₦200,000 - Salary ₦30,000 - Interest ₦10,000 = ₦160,000 remaining. Half of ₦160,000 = ₦80,000. A's total = ₦30,000 + ₦10,000 + ₦80,000 = ₦120,000.",
    full: "Partnership profit allocation follows a specific order. First, any partner salaries are allocated (these are not expenses, but appropriations). Second, interest on capital is allocated. Third, interest on drawings may be charged (deducted from partners). Finally, the remaining profit (or loss) is shared according to the profit-sharing ratio. In this example: Net profit = ₦200,000. Step 1: Allocate A's salary: ₦30,000. Step 2: Allocate A's interest on capital: ₦10,000. Total allocated so far = ₦40,000. Remaining profit = ₦200,000 - ₦40,000 = ₦160,000. This remaining profit is shared equally (50:50). A gets half: ₦160,000 × 1/2 = ₦80,000. B gets the other ₦80,000. A's total = Salary ₦30,000 + Interest ₦10,000 + Share of profit ₦80,000 = ₦120,000. B's total = Share of profit ₦80,000. The journal entry to record this is: Debit Profit and Loss Appropriation Account (total ₦200,000), Credit A's Current Account (₦120,000), Credit B's Current Account (₦80,000)."
