    e: "The partnership deed (or partnership agreement) is a legal document that sets out the terms of the partnership, including profit-sharing ratios, capital contributions, partner salaries, interest rates, and procedures for admitting or retiring partners.",
    full: "The partnership deed (also called the partnership agreement or articles of partnership) is a crucial document for any partnership. It should include: the names of the partners and the name of the partnership, the date of formation, the capital contributed by each partner, the profit and loss sharing ratio, any salaries or commissions to be paid to partners, interest rates on capital and drawings, procedures for admitting new partners, procedures for partner retirement or death, how disputes will be resolved, how the partnership can be dissolved, and any other special terms agreed by the partners. If there is no partnership deed, or if the deed is silent on an issue, the Partnership Act (or similar legislation) provides default rules. Default rules typically include: profits and losses shared equally, no interest on capital, no partner salaries, interest on drawings at a specified rate, and no interest on loans from partners beyond a specified rate. Having a clear partnership deed helps prevent disputes and ensures smooth operation of the partnership. It is strongly recommended that all partnerships have a written deed."
