    full: "Partnership law provides default rules for partnerships that do not have a written partnership deed, or where the deed does not cover certain matters. Under these default rules: Profits and losses are shared equally among partners (regardless of capital contributions). No interest is paid on partners' capital. No salaries are paid to partners for their work. Interest on drawings (money taken out) may be charged at a specified rate (often 5% or the bank rate). Partners who lend money to the partnership beyond their capital are entitled to interest at the rate of 5% per annum (or the bank rate). These default rules emphasize that partners are expected to have a written agreement if they want special terms. Without an agreement, the default rules apply. Many partnerships choose to have a written deed to specify different arrangements. For example, a partner who contributes more capital but works less might want interest on capital to compensate them, while a partner who works more might want a salary. These can only be agreed in the partnership deed."
