    full: "In partnerships, the profit-sharing ratio is also used to share losses, unless the partnership deed specifies otherwise. This is because losses are the negative of profits - if you share profits 3:2, you also share losses 3:2. In this example, the ratio is 3:2 (total 5 parts). A gets 3/5 of the loss: 3/5 × ₦50,000 = ₦30,000. B gets 2/5 of the loss: 2/5 × ₦50,000 = ₦20,000. The entry to record this would be: Debit A's Current Account (₦30,000) and Debit B's Current Account (₦20,000), Credit Profit and Loss Appropriation Account (₦50,000). This reduces the partners' equity by the amount of the loss. If the loss is larger than the partners' current account balances, it may need to be recorded as a debit balance in the current account (meaning the partner owes money to the partnership) or may reduce the capital account. Partners may be required to contribute additional capital to cover losses, depending on the partnership agreement and legal requirements."
